{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a complex string/bitstring construction problem involving prefix-free properties and constraints on bitstring lengths. It requires finding a way to extend existing bitstrings such that no bitstring is a prefix of another, even after truncation, which implies a specific structure related to Huffman coding or prefix codes.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "prefix_structure_analyzer",
      "instructions": "Analyze the constraints of the problem: given a set of bitstrings, find the minimum length extension such that no bitstring is a prefix of another. Determine if this can be modeled as building a binary tree where the given bitstrings are nodes and we must ensure no node is an ancestor of another. Specifically, identify the mathematical condition for a set of bitstrings to be prefix-free and how truncation affects this."
    },
    {
      "label": "greedy_construction_strategist",
      "instructions": "Develop a greedy algorithm or a priority queue-based approach to extend the bitstrings. The goal is to minimize the maximum length or the total length (depending on the specific optimization target in the problem) by appending bits such that the prefix-free property is maintained. Determine the optimal order in which to process bitstrings of different lengths."
    },
    {
      "label": "complexity_and_implementation_verifier",
      "instructions": "Given the constraints of USACO Platinum (typically N up to 10^5 or similar), evaluate the time complexity of the proposed greedy strategy. Check if a segment tree, Fenwick tree, or a specialized Trie structure is required to efficiently manage the bitstring extensions and ensure the prefix-free property is checked in logarithmic time."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the prefix-free mathematical conditions with the greedy construction strategy to form a complete algorithm. Use the complexity analysis to ensure the algorithm fits within the time limits, likely involving a Trie or a priority queue to manage the bitstring extensions."
}

